<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">socat tcp-listen:8001,reuseaddr,fork tcp:localhost:8000</code></p>

<p>this is great since you do not have to have a local ssh server running. For the server listening on port 8000, the connection will appear as coming from the proxy, not the original client. Youâ€™d need to useÂ DNAT approachesÂ (but which requires superuser privileges) for the server to be able to tell whoâ€™s the client</p>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">ssh -g -L 8001:localhost:8000 -f -N user@remote-server.com</code>
This forwards the local port 8001 on your workstation to the localhost address on remote-server.com port 8000.â€¨-gÂ means allow other clients on my network to connect to port 8001 on my workstation. Otherwise only local clients on your workstation can connect to the forwarded port.â€¨-NÂ means all I am doing is forwarding ports, donâ€™t start a shell.â€¨-fÂ means fork into background after a successful SSH connection and log-in.â€¨Port 8001 will stay open for many connections, until ssh dies or is killed. If you happen to be on Windows, the excellent SSH client PuTTY can do this as well. Use 8001 as the local port and localhost:8000 and the destination and add a local port forwarding in settings. You can add it after a successful connect with PuTTY.</p>

